00:51.800 --> 00:55.120
components within the TCB, the trusted computing base.

00:55.760 --> 00:59.680
These next few slides are where we delve into each of these pieces in a little more detail.

01:01.280 --> 01:04.880
Now, we have to start with, of course, what's the subject versus what's an object?

01:05.360 --> 01:11.040
And the subject is the active entity. It's a person or it's a process. It's something

01:11.040 --> 01:17.760
trying to actively access an object. And an object is the passive entity. It's

01:17.760 --> 01:22.240
whatever is being accessed. It can be another process. It could be a database,

01:22.400 --> 01:26.800
a sharepoint site, a hard drive, could even be a building or a system.

01:27.680 --> 01:34.240
This is the object. And the reference monitor concept is this whole idea that we want to be

01:34.240 --> 01:41.600
able to mediate or control a subject's access to an object, control and mediate that access

01:41.600 --> 01:46.880
based on a set of rules. And all this is logged and monitored. This is the reference monitor

01:47.440 --> 01:53.040
concept. And of course, for this concept to be effective, we have to implement it.

01:53.680 --> 01:58.320
And so a security kernel is the implementation of the reference monitor concept.

01:59.200 --> 02:04.080
And a security kernel can be anything. It can be hardware, firmware, software,

02:04.080 --> 02:09.680
anything that's actually controlling a subject's access to an object is fundamentally a security

02:10.320 --> 02:16.640
kernel. So a padlock, a door badge system, a login mechanism on a computer system,

02:17.200 --> 02:21.920
a operating system controlling access to components with the operating system,

02:21.920 --> 02:26.640
a hypervisor controlling which virtual machines can connect to which of the underlying

02:26.640 --> 02:30.960
physical hardware. All of these are fundamentally security kernels.

02:32.800 --> 02:38.080
And the RMZ and the implementation of which the security kernel has to demonstrate

02:38.080 --> 02:43.920
three properties to be a good security kernel. First, completeness. And this is about not being

02:43.920 --> 02:50.080
able to bypass the rules. The subject should not be able to bypass and directly access an object

02:50.080 --> 02:57.600
and bypass the mediation. So completeness impossible to bypass. Isolation, the rules are

02:57.600 --> 03:04.400
tamper proof that can only be changed modified by an authorized individual. And verifiability.

03:04.960 --> 03:10.800
How do you verify that this security kernel is actually working correctly, typically by logging

03:10.800 --> 03:15.200
and monitoring the activity that's occurring, which subjects are getting to access to which

03:15.200 --> 03:22.880
objects and which circumstances. And the final piece that we'll talk about here is the tcb.

03:23.520 --> 03:27.200
And this is where we'll spend a minute here because there's often questions on the tcb and it

03:27.200 --> 03:33.040
often confuses people a little bit. So here's the perfect definition of the tcb. It's the

03:33.040 --> 03:38.720
totality of protection mechanisms within an architecture. So what does that actually mean?

03:38.720 --> 03:45.520
Let's start with the word totality. What does totality mean? It means all everything, the assembly,

03:45.520 --> 03:52.640
the collection, all of the components. So here's a really big hint for the exam. If you see anything

03:52.640 --> 04:00.080
that says any word that means all the collection, the assembly, the everything related to the

04:00.080 --> 04:07.200
protection mechanisms, that is the tcb. So it's all of the mechanisms that are responsible for

04:07.200 --> 04:13.200
protecting a system. Think of it this way. Picture any type of architecture. Let's take a laptop

04:13.200 --> 04:17.360
as an example. You might be sitting in front of one right now. Your laptop is going to have all

04:17.360 --> 04:22.160
starts of components in it. You're going to have a CPU ram. You're going to have a hard drive.

04:22.160 --> 04:26.400
You're going to have USB ports. You're going to have an operating system and all sorts of

04:26.400 --> 04:30.400
applications and firmware. These are all the components within the architecture.

04:31.200 --> 04:35.760
Some of those components are responsible for the security of a system. Things like your anti-malware

04:35.760 --> 04:43.920
software, your security kernels, your host-based firewall. So the tcb is that subset of if you take

04:43.920 --> 04:48.960
all of the components, it's the subset that are responsible for security. That is the tcb.

04:49.600 --> 04:54.720
And so when we say you know what can make up the tcb, it's anything that is responsible for

04:54.720 --> 04:59.520
security. Could be hardware, could be firmware, could be software, could be processes.

05:00.240 --> 05:05.200
So that's the tcb. And the next few modules will start to talk through a bunch of different

05:05.200 --> 05:11.520
components that we have within modern computing systems. And some of these components are in fact

05:11.520 --> 05:22.320
security kernels and some of them are components within the tcb.

